tlichen Konflikten um Nachhaltigkeit.  aSustainability has become a leading principle of social change that combines different objectives - be it green capitalism based on ecological modernization or a socio-ecological transformation that could ring in a post-capitalist era. The social dimensions of sustainability as well as the paradoxes relating to a sustainable development in global capitalism are examined in this programmatic text by Sighard Neckel and his research team in Hamburg. Basic sociological perspectives of sustainability are the subject, as are prospects of concrete fields of a critical-reflexive social research on the social conflicts centering around sustainability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aSocial ecology. 0aSociologyxResearch. 0aSustainability. 4aGesellschaft. 4aNatur. 4aPostkapitalismus. 4aReflexive Sozialforschung. 4aSoziologie. 4aSoziologische Theorie. 4aUmweltsoziologie. 4aÖkologie. 4aÖkologische Modernisierung. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aEcological Modernization.  aEcology.  aEnvironmental Sociology.  aNature.  aPostcapitalism.  aReflexive Social Research.  aSociety.  aSociological Theory.  aSociology.1 aBesedovsky, Natalia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBesedovsky, Natalia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoddenberg, Moritz, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBoddenberg, Moritz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasenfratz, Martina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeckel, Sighar